      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA152-kiḷavi">itu maṭal valitta talaivaṉ muṉṉilaip puṟamoḻiyākat tōḻi kēṭpac colliyatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is what HE, who enforced the palmyra stem [horse], said so that the confidante would hear [it] when there was slander against him.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA152">
<l>            maṭalē kāman tanta talarē</l>
<l>            miṭaipū verukki ṉalartan taṉṟē</l>
<l>            yilaṅkukatir maḻuṅki yelvicumpu paṭarap</l>
<l>            pulamputan taṉṟē pukaṉṟucey maṇṭila</l>
<l>            mellām tantataṉ ṟalaiyum paiyeṉa </l>
<l>            vaṭantai tuvalai tūvak kuṭampaip</l>
<l>            peṭaiyuṇa raṉṟi liyaṅkukura laḷaiik</l>
<l>            kaṅkuluṅ kaiyaṟa vantaṉ</l>
<l>            ṟiyāṅkā kuveṉko laḷiyēṉ yāṉē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Desire has brought [me] the palmyra horse.</l>
<l rend="indent4">The blossom</l>
<l>of Yarcum in close-set flowers has brought [me] gossip.</l>
<l>The desired(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">pukaṉṟucey</term> is explained by T.V.G. as a compound verb "to be desired". As such it is not to be found in the TL. Another way of understanding the phrase might be to interpret <term xml:lang="ta">pukaṉṟu</term> not as an absolutive, but as a short n.a. verbal noun. Then we would have an attribute "the [sun-]disk that does what is desirable".</note> [sun]-disk has brought [me] loneliness,</l>
<l rend="indent">the shining beams having become dim while the light pervades</l>
<l rend="indent3">in the sky.</l>
<l rend="indent2">On top of what has been brought by all [of these],</l>
<l>night too has come to stop [all] doing,</l>
<l rend="indent">mingling with the Aṉṟil's stirring voice that perceives [its] female</l>
<l rend="indent2">in the nest, while the northern wind spatters spray, gently.</l>
<l>What will become of me, pitiable I?</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
          </body>
        </text>
